{"input": {"source_code": "@SuppressWarnings(\"unchecked\")\npublic static Map<String, String> deserializeOffsetMap(String lastSourceOffset) throws IOException {\n  Map<String, String> offsetMap;\n  if (lastSourceOffset == null || lastSourceOffset.isEmpty()) {    \n    offsetMap = new HashMap<>();  \n  } else {\n    offsetMap = JSON_MAPPER.readValue(lastSourceOffset, Map.class);  \n  }\n  return offsetMap;\n}\n", "repo_info": {"repo": "streamsets/datacollector", "path": "stagesupport/src/main/java/com/.../OffsetUtil.java", "function_name": "OffsetUtil.deserializeOffsetMap"}}, "output": "The provided code is a static method named `deserializeOffsetMap` in the class `OffsetUtil`. This method takes a single parameter: `lastSourceOffset`, which is of type `String`.\n\nHere's an explanation of what this method does:\n\n1. The method first imports and uses a JSON mapper, presumably from a library like Jackson or Gson, to parse JSON strings into Java objects.\n\n2. It declares a variable `offsetMap` of type `Map<String, String>`. This is the map that will hold the deserialized data.\n\n3. The method then checks if `lastSourceOffset` is either null or an empty string. If it is, it initializes `offsetMap` as a new `HashMap<>`.\n\n4. If `lastSourceOffset` is not null and not an empty string, the method uses the JSON mapper to deserialize the `lastSourceOffset` string into a generic `Map`. The deserialized map is then assigned to `offsetMap`.\n\n5. Finally, it returns the `offsetMap`.\n\nIn summary, this function takes in a serialized offset as a string, checks if it's null or empty, and either initializes an empty map or deserializes the input string into a map of strings. It uses JSON_MAPPER for deserialization which is likely a JSON mapper instance from a library like Jackson or Gson.\n\nThis method is useful when you have offsets stored in a serialized format (like JSON) and need to convert them back into a Java Map object for further processing.", "metric": 0.2688644688644689}
